Why is Any used as extension mechanism and not an abstract element?
1) If an abstract element was used, derived classes could still add whatever is needed. 2) Using Any one no longer needs to extend a specific version of the (extension) property. Thus extensions will be reusable across different versions of this specification.
If extensions were created for an abstract element, then these extensions will - per the schema definition and namespace import - be only valid for one major.minor version of the specification (like SWES 1.0, 1.1 etc). Each and every extension would have to be updated in order to port it to a new specification major.minor version. This can be avoided by decoupling the extensions from specific versions of this specification.
However, care must be taken when designing extensions. Compare with extensions made in SOAP based applications. Support for extensions needs to be indicated by the service. Extensions are either optional (i.e. if the client uses one, the service may ignore it) or mandatory (then the service must understand it - compare with SOAP mustUnderstand header). Optional extensions are the safest way to test a new mechanism without breaking the core model and - if the extension turns out to be widely applicable - it can be integrated into the core or mandatory extension.

Why is there no explicit topic hierarchy?
We began modeling such a hierarchy. But when thinking about how this structure could be mapped to the topic namespace and topic set defined in WS-Topics we recognized that we would break the modeling approach suggested there. In addition the approach from WS-Notification is not that difficult to understand - the subtleties of the WS-N specs only need to be explained more clearly.
We also promote the reuse of existing interfaces and data types.

1) producerEndpoint property is mandatory, so each service shall indicate where clients need to send subscription requests to.
2) topicSet property is required for all services that allow subscribing to notifications.
3) fixedTopicSet: service needs to identify whether the topic set is fixed or not.
4,5,6) Dialects are required to indicate which filter functionality a service supports. Filters can be applied when subscribing for specific notifications. Not every dialect may be applicable to each topic. This could be indicated by adding topic metadata (in the topic namespace and/or topic set; in the former this could be a metdatada element added to the documentation element, while in the latter case it could be an attribute that lists the dialect URIs).

UML:TaggedValue.value:
Usage of the validTime property allows us to update not only the current but also past descriptions. Of course, care must be taken as to how this should work (replace past descriptions only completely) ...
The whole description should be provided and replaced, no partial updates are allowed
The service should send out a notification that this update has been applied if it is successful - <font color="#ff0000">notification type TBD</font>
